text: This movie wasn't what I expected. I read the description without watching the trailer. I read the description too quickly and only saw a few keywords like spy, encryption etc. I thought yes this going to be a futuristic, action, spy movie.  But when the movie started I knew I had made a mistake, it was a British movie, and started off in Manchester.  I came out of the cinema feeling like I had just paid to watch a documentary, if only I had read the description properly and watched the trailer beforehand.  Some people were laughing at so many parts of the movie like it was a comedy, I mean what they were laughing at wasn't even that funny. Like peas and carrots WTF? And that part when he tells a story after giving apples to the other guys who were working with them, a few people laughed really hard to that, it wasnt even funny.  One other thing I noticed, was yesterday when I watched the movie, is how much seats were empty, there weren't many people watching this movie, which was unusual because normally its quite full. The cinema car park was full too, it was clear it wasn't a very popular movie. The target audience for this is quite small and limited.  I was expecting an american hollywood movie as they are always good. This may offend some but its true, I don't think British movies will ever be on Hollywoods level. I mean just look at the beginning of the trailer, it has to be approved by America.

text: Author dr Marek Grajek 1918 â€“ 1939 1918 - Arthur Scherbius applies for a patent for the Enigma cipher machine.   Scherbius' Enigma patentâ€”U.S. Patent 1,657,411, granted in 1928. 1926 - Enigma is used by the German navy. 1928 - Enigma is used by the German land forces. 1929, January â€“ a cryptology course is launched at PoznaÅ„ University, it is attended, among others, by Marian Rejewski, Jerzy RÃ³Å¼ycki and Henryk Zygalski. 1929, summer â€“ having completed the cryptology course, Jerzy RÃ³Å¼ycki and Henryk Zygalski start to work at the Cipher Office branch in PoznaÅ„. 1930, summer â€“ Marian Rejewski, after returning from GÃ¶ttingen, also starts to work at the Cipher Office. 1932, september â€“ the team of the PoznaÅ„ branch of Cipher Office is transferred to Warsaw. 1932, October â€“ Maksymilian CiÄ™Å¼ki entrusts Marian Rejewski with the task of breaking the Enigma code. 1932, December â€“ Marian Rejewski recreates the machine and breaks first messages encrypted with Enigma. 1933 â€“AVA company builds about a dozen copies of Enigma, and decryption of Enigma messages starts at full speed. 1935 - the Polish team creates a cyclometer â€“ the first electromechanical device supporting the decryption process. 1938, autumn â€“ the Germans make some further modifications in the way Enigma is used and add two new rotors to the machine. 1938, November â€“Marian Rejewski responds to the new challenge and builds â€œa bombâ€. At the same time, Henryk Zygalski designs his method of sheets. 1939, January â€“ a British-French-Polish cryptologic conference is held in Paris. Some British participant of the conference describes the Poles as 'foolish and ignorant'. 1939, July â€“ the second trilateral conference in Warsaw. The Poles disclose the secret of their successes in breaking the Enigma codes and share with the future Allies their entire knowledge about the methods used in decrypting the Enigma codes. 1939, August â€“ the news from Poland directly affect the decisons of the Brits to recruit mathematicians as well as expand their cryptologic centre in Bletchley Park. 1939, September â€“ the outbreak of war, the evacuation of the Cipher Bureau via Romania to France.  Zygalski sheet  1939 - 1945  1939, October â€“ the team of cryptologists, due to some political disagreement, is denided joining the Polish Armed Forces. The cryptologists are subject to the French command. 1939, autumn â€“ the British have difficulties using the knowledge disclosed by the Poles. The French, however, refuse to delegate, even temporarily, any of the Poles to help overcome the deadlock. 1940, January â€“Alan Turing brings Zygalski sheets to France. They have been prepared in Great Britain as specified by the instructions from Poles. On 15th January the Poles break the first Enigma message in World War II with the use of the sheets. 1940, April â€“the Polish and British teams successfully break the ciphers of Enigma during the Norwegian Campaign. 1940, May â€“ the Germans change the manner of use of Enigma before the attack on Benelux and France â€“ the allied cryptologists are temporarily helpless. 1940, June â€“ evacuation of the Polish team to the south of France and then to North Africa. At the same time in Great Britain John Herivel overcomes the crisis in decryption. 1940, August â€“ on the brink of the Battle of Britain, the first Turing bomb, designed on the basis of the earlier Rejewskiâ€™s bomb, but much more efficient, arrives in Bletchley Park.  The first Turing bomb 1940, September â€“ decrypted messages of Luftwaffe communication network support the British in the decisive phase of the Battle of Britain . 1940, Octoberâ€“ the French decide to transfer the Polish cryptologists to the part of France free from occupation and to organise a semi-conspirational cryptologic intelligence station near UzÃ¨s. 1941, Spring â€“ the British begin to break the ciphers of German units that are being organised in North Africa. 1941, Aprilâ€“ thanks to the documents found on board of a German boat off the coast of Norway, the British break the Enigma Kriegsmarine ciphers for the first time. 1941, May â€“ the control of the British over the Kriegsmarine ciphers is strengthened even more thanks to the documents found on board of a captured U-110 submarine. 1942, January â€“ Jerzy RÃ³Å¼ycki and two other members of the Polish team die in a ship crash on the Mediterranean.  LamoriciÃ¨re â€“ the passenger ship that RÃ³Å¼ycki was travelling on 1942, February â€“ the fleet of German submarines introduces a 4-rotor Enigma. The British lose their ability to break its ciphers and begin to suffer disastrous losses in the Battle of the Atlantic. 1942, November â€“  in reaction to the allied invasion in North Africa, the Germans take over southern France. The Polish station is closed down with urgency, and its personnel await in conspiracy for a chance to escape from the occupied territory. 1942, December â€“ a discovery on board of a submarine makes it possible to overcome the deadlock in decryption of the 4-rotor Enigma. 1943, February and March â€“ the members of the Polish team try to cross the green border with Spain. Some of them manage to do that, but the commander of the group, Lt. Col. Langer, and his deputy, Major CiÄ™Å¼ki, betrayed by the French are captured by the Germans. 1943, Summer â€“ Marian Rejewski and Henryk Zygalski, after a period of internment in Spain, reach Great Britain through Portugal and Spain. In Great Britain, however, they are not allowed to work in the centre, which came into being thanks to their successes in attacks on Enigma. Until the end of the war they work on solving less important German ciphers, mostly manual ciphers of Waffen SS. 1943, Summer â€“ cryptologic bombs designed in the USA, a lot faster than the British ones, are started to be used. Thanks to them, most Enigma ciphers, also those of the 4-rotor model, are broken quickly and efficiently. 1944, Spring â€“ Langer and CiÄ™Å¼ki are held in an internment camp in Eisenberg castle (the territory of the present Czech Republic). A committee of German radio-intelligence services pays them an unexpected visit to interrogate the Polish officers. The Poles manage to mislead the interrogators, and keep the success of Enigma decryption by the Allies secret. 1944, Summer â€“ the Germans begin to suspect that the Enigma codes are being broken and introduce new devices making the decryption even more difficult, among others, the â€œUhrâ€ unit and a reflector with variable wiring (the so-called UKD). This, however, makes it more of an inconvenience rather than a significant barrier for the Allies to decrypt the German codes.  Module â€Uhrâ€ 1945, May â€“ Langer and CiÄ™Å¼ki are liberated by the Americans in the liberation of the camp. They return to London where they receive a cold welcome. 1945 â€“ immediately after the end of World War II, the decryption of Enigma, one of the biggest secrets of that war, transforms smoothly into one of the biggest secrets of the just-started Cold War. The mathematical principles developed by the Poles to enable breaking the ciphers produced by rotor machines, continue to be valid, and therefore must remain secret.  After 1946  1946 â€“ Marian Rejewski returns to the country, when he must sacrifice all his ambitions to ensure safety to himself and his family. Henryk Zygalski remains in Great Britain. Although he holds a university degree, his Polish diploma is not recognised in Britain. To be allowed to teach mathematics at British schools, he has to repeat his studies. 1956 â€“ in the USA, one of the bombs from the period of World War II, used until then to break the messages of the East Germany police, encrypted with Enigma, makes its last run. 1967 â€“ having retired, Marian Rejewski writes down his memoirs of the pre-war work and deposits them at the Military History Institute. A later reference, of  a Polish historian, to that book and the breaking of Enigma is received with disbelief.  A copy of Memories by Marian Rejewski 1968 â€“ a couple of British historians hint in their works at breaking of the Enigma code and the role of the Poles in this operation. text: The German plugboard-equipped Enigma became the Third Reich's principal crypto-system. It was broken by the Polish General Staff's Cipher Bureau in December 1932â€”with the aid of French-supplied intelligence material that had been obtained from a German spy. Shortly before the outbreak of World War II, the Polish Cipher Bureau initiated the French and British into its Enigma-breaking techniques and technology at a conference held in Warsaw. It was broken thanks to French , English , Polish From this beginning, the British Government Code and Cypher School (GC&CS) at Bletchley Park built up an extensive cryptanalytic facility. Initially, the decryption was mainly of Luftwaffe and a few Army messages, as the Kriegsmarine (German navy) employed much more secure procedures for using Enigma. Alan Turing, a Cambridge University mathematician and logician, provided much of the original thinking that led to the design of the cryptanalytical Bombe machines and the eventual breaking of naval Enigma. However, the German Navy introduced an Enigma version with a fourth rotor for its U-boats resulting in a prolonged period when these messages could not be decrypted.

text: "From September 1938, Turing had been working part-time with the GC&CS, the British code breaking organisation. He concentrated on cryptanalysis of the Enigma, with Dilly Knox, a senior GC&CS codebreaker.[46] Soon after the July 1939 Warsaw meeting at which the Polish Cipher Bureau had provided the British and French with the details of the wiring of Enigma rotors and their method of decrypting Enigma code messages, Turing and Knox started to work on a less fragile approach to the problem.[47] The Polish method relied on an insecure indicator procedure that the Germans were likely to change, which they did in May 1940. Turing's approach was more general, using crib-based decryption for which he produced the functional specification of the bombe (an improvement of the Polish Bomba).[48]" Wikipedia / Alan Turing  "Without the Polish assistance, British cryptologists would, at the very least, have been considerably delayed in reading Enigma. Author Hugh Sebag-Montefiore concludes that substantial breaks into German Army and Air Force Enigma ciphers by the British would have occurred only after November 1941 at the earliest, after an Enigma machine and key lists had been captured, and similarly into Naval Enigma only after late 1942.[46] Former Bletchley Park cryptologist Gordon Welchman goes further, writing that the Army and Air Force Enigma section, Hut 6, "would never have gotten off the ground if we had not learned from the Poles, in the nick of time, the details both of the German military... Enigma machine, and of the operating procedures that were in use."[47]  Intelligence gained from solving high-level German ciphersâ€”intelligence codenamed "Ultra" by the British and Americansâ€”came chiefly from Enigma decrypts. While the exact contribution of Ultra intelligence to Allied victory is disputed, Kozaczuk and Straszak note that "it is widely believed that Ultra saved the world at least two years of war and possibly prevented Hitler from winning."[48] The English historian Sir Harry Hinsley, who worked at Bletchley Park, similarly assessed it as having "shortened the war by not less than two years and probably by four years".[49] The availability of Ultra was, at the least, due largely to the earlier Polish breaking of Enigma." from Wikipedia / Marian Rejewski

text: Since there's an argument about this, I'm going to lay it out flat. The Enigma machine had been used by the Germans since the 1920's. The Polish cracked it by reverse engineering it. However, then Enigma was redesigned, several times in fact, by the Germans, and unfortunately the Poles couldn't keep up. The Poles went to British intelligence. British intelligence used the algorithm originally developed by the Poles to build the machine seen in the film (which the film mentions btw), which could calculate Enigma's codes. The big difference between the Polish variation and the one seen in the film was that the Polish variation was hand done. The Brittish invented essentially the first computer which could keep up with the German changes to the codes.

text: Very well acted film, but historically totally inaccurate. A missed opportunity because the true story of Turing is fascinating, so why they had to make up so much baffles me. The examples of mistakes are so many that I will only pick a few; Turing had nothing to do with Joan Clarke's appointment, never met Stewart Menzies, never worked with Caiurncross, never discovered Cairncross was a Soviet agent (how could he? He never even knew the man), got on very well with Denniston, Denniston had great faith in Turing's machines and never tried to block their development, Turing only did the theoretical work on his machine, it was Tommy Flowers who built it- it is a disgrace that Flowers gets no mention in the film. Far from being one of a select small team, Bletchley had several thousand staff. Turing and his team had no say in what happened to the Intelligence...and so on and so on.
